The heart, lungs, spleen, liver and kidneys are together known as the five Zang-organs.
Extraordinary Fu-organs, unlike ordinary ones, comprise six organs, namely, the brain, marrow, bone, vessel, gallbladder and uterus.
The heart governs the vessels and blood circulation and the mind takes Qi-blood as its material basis.
The normal circulation of all the blood in the vessels depends on the impulse of the heart-Qi, by which blood is transported to all parts of the body for nutritive purpose.
The vessels, also called channels, are the house of blood.
The tongue serves two main functions: that of discriminating tastes and that of aiding in speech, the performance of which depends on the heart's physiological functions in governing blood and vessels and in controlling mental activities.
Therefore, if the heart functions properly, the tongue must be ruddy-lustrous and soft-nimble, taste sensations keen and speech fluent.
Their main jobs are to dominate Qi and respiration, fulfil the dispersing and descending functions, participate in regulating water metabolism, and communicate with numerous vessels to achieve coordination of functional activities of the whole body, assisting the heart in maintaining normal circulation of Qi-blood.
The lungs, which extend upward to the larynx and open into the nose, are related outward to the skin and its hairs.
Pectoral Qi is mainly produced by combination of fresh air inhaled into the lungs with food essence derived from the spleen and stomach.
Whether or not the lungs function properly directly influences the formation of pectoral Qi and Qi of the whole body as well.
The breathing movement of the lungs itself is a manifestation of lifting-lowering and entering-exiting of Qi, in which the lungs play an important regulatory role by their rhythmical respiration.
Since the lungs dominate Qi of the whole body and control respiration, the circulation of blood depends to a certain extent on the spread and coordination of the lung-Qi.
Since the lungs dominate Qi and perform the functions of dispersing outward defensive Qi and sending the essence to the skin and vellus hairs, they are closely related to the skin and its hairs.
When the lungs function normally, the skin becomes compact and body resistance enhanced.
The surplus fluids are turned into sweat and urine to be removed from the body under the functioning of the lungs and kidneys.
Thus, normal functioning of the spleen in this respect can prevent body fluids from accumulating and such pathological changes as dampness, phlegm and water-retention from occurring.
On the contrary, dysfunction of the spleen leads to failure to transport-transform the nutrients from foodstuff regularly and failure to supply Qi-blood, thus giving rise to such symptoms as listlessness, weakness, dizziness, abdominal distension, and loose stool.
In case of the spleen's dysfunction in transportation and transformation, the Qi-blood will be insufficient and the commanding action be reduced, thereby producing various kinds of chronic hemorrhage.
The liver's function of governing normal flow of Qiis threefold.
If the liver functions properly in this respect, the normal functioning of Qi as well as Qi-blood, free flow of channels, and the proper functioning of Zang-Fu organs and other-structures will ensue as a result.
The proper functioning of the liver in governing normal flow of Qi greatly influences the lifting-lowering function of the spleen and stomach.
For instance, dysfunction of the liver can impair the function of the spleen and stomach in lifting clear Qi and lowering turbid Qi, resulting in the symptoms due to an attack of the spleen or stomach by the hyperactive liver-Qi.
The emotional activities are chiefly dominated by the heart, but they are also closely related to the liver.
The main functions of the kidneys are:(1) to store essence, (2) to dominate growth, development and reproduction, and (3) to govern water metabolism and reception of air.
Since the essence stored in the kidneys is the major material foundation for the body's growth, development and reproduction, hypofunction of the kidneys in storing the essence may not only lead to such symptoms as spermatorrhea, nocturnal emission and premature ejaculation due to unconsolidation of the kidney-Qi, but also impair normal growth, development and reproduction of the body resulting from deficiency of the kidney-essence.
As a result, abundance of the kidney-essence leads to the plenitude of the bone marrow, resulting in the sturdy-robust skeleton and agile-powerful motions of the limbs.
Under the actions of the stomach-Qi and stomach-fluid the food mass in the stomach is preliminarily digested into the chyme and then is carried into the small intestine to be further digested.
This is because of the fact that foodstuff is the source for the production of Qi-blood which is the material basis for vital functions of the Zang-Fu organs.
So failure of descending of the stomach-Qimay cause the adverse rising of the stomach-Qi. marked by belching with acid regurgitation, nausea, vomiting, hiccup, etc.
Clinically, doctors attach inuch importance to it and usually regard"preserving the stomach-Qi" as an important principle of treatment.
The small intestine has the exterior-interior relation with the heart because of the interconnection between their channels
On the other hand, the function of the small intestine in digesting means that this organ further digests the foodstuff partially digested in the stomach and converts it into refined nutritious substances.
For this reason, dysfunction of the small intestine may cause diarrhea resulting from "sinking of clearQi."
The disorder of the urinary bladder usually manifests itself by frequency and urgency of urination, urodynia, oliguria, dysuria, dribbling urination, even anuresis, enuresis. or incontinence of urine, and so on.
It is exterior-interiorly related to the pericardium by their channels.
If the water passages namely, Tri-Jiao, are blocked, the distributive and regulative functions of the lungs, spleen, kidneys and others are hard to fulfil.
The middle-Jiao refers usually to the epigastrium below the diaphragm and above the umbilicus, including such viscera as the spleen, stomach, liver and gallbladder.
Conversely, the pathogenic heat of the small intestine may bring about flaring-up of the heart-fire along its own channel, manifested by dysphoria, crimson tongue, oral ulceration and so on.
The spleen corresponds to dampness, while the stomach to dryness.
In case of sufficiency of the kidney-Qi, the kidneys fulfil their reserving function normally and the urinary bladder functions to open and close at the right moment. However, in case of insufficiency of the kidney-Qi, disturbance in Qi transformation will occur, followed by failure of the kidneys to fulfil their reserving function and by abnormal opening-closing of the urinary bladder, marked by oliguria or incontinence of urine, or enuresis, frequent urination, etc.
The link between these two Zang-organs embodies the interdependence and interaction between Qi and blood.
Therefore, the relation between the heart and the spleen can be manifested chiefly in two aspects: formation of blood and its circulation.
Meanwhile, only when the liver functions properly in controlling normal flow of Qi, accompanied by regular functioning of Qi, can the blood flow smoothly.
Pathologically, inability of the liver to store blood leads to failure of the heart to govern blood, thus resulting in irregular flow of blood.
In the former case, owing to respiratory function of the lungs and transporting-transforming function of the spleen, fresh air inhaled in the lungs and food essence derived from the spleen and stomach provide the main material basis for the formation of vital Qi of the body.
As for pathological connections, insufficiency of the spleen-Qi usually brings about insufficiency of the lung-Qi; dysfunction of the spleen in transport leads to disorder of water metabolism and stagnancy of fluids, accumulated into phlegm and fluid-retention which mostly impair the dispersing and descending functions of the lungs, resulting in a morbid condition marked by dyspnea and cough with copious sputum.
In regard to water metabolism the lungs, as "the upper source of fluid" rely upon the kidney-Qi for support (especially its steaming activity). Conversely, the kidneys which dominate metabolism of body fluids also require support from the lungs (especially their function in descending Qi and clearing water passages).
As to pathological changes, impairment of the dispersing and descending function of the lungs and their failure to clear and regulate water passages must affect the kidneys, thus giving rise to oliguria and even edema; while disturbance in functioning of the kidney-Qi with the retained fluid overflowing upward results in dyspnea, or gasping cough with inability to lie flat.
Moreover, there is a close relation between the liver and spleen as far as formation, storage and circulation of blood are concerned.
The liver governs normal flow of Qi and the kidneys, storage of essence, so both restrain and oppose each other and yet complement each other, all mainly manifested by such physiological functions as menstruation and seminal emission.
Consequently, production of Qi-blood by the spleen depends on the warming-invigorating action of the kidneys.
In addition, aided by other Zang-Fu organs, the spleen and the kidneys coordinate their respective functions (in conveying fluid and dominating water) so as to maintain the balance in metabolism of body fluids.
For example, congenital defect and weakness of the warming-invigorating action of the kidneys may impair the function of the spleen in generating Qi-blood, whereas lack of proper care after. birth and deficiency of Qi-blood produced by the spleen may lead to deficiency of the kidney-essence caused by failure of the kidneys to store the essence from other Zang-Fu-organs.
As regards the source or formation of Qi, it is closely related to the physiological functions of the kidneys, spleen, stomach and lungs in addition to innate andowment, acquired diet nutrition, and natural environment.
The defensive function of Qi is reflected mainly in protecting the body surface against external pathogens.
For instance, the essence derived from the food and drink is transformed into Qi, blood and body fluids, the body fluids after being metabolized are converted into sweat and urine, and the residues of food after digestion and absorption are turned into feces, etc. All these processes are concrete manifestations of the transforming action of Qi.
The primordial Qi possesses the functions of promoting growth and development of the body, warming and activating all Zang-Fu organs, channels and collaterals and other structures.
It is distributed in the vessels as the component parts of blood.
As opposed to pathogens, the vital Qi is the healthy Qi of the body.
Since they both are derived from the food essence, the quality of the nutrients taken in and the functional state of the spleen and stomach directly influence the formation of blood.
Moreover, the essence can also be transformed into blood.
As is said inNan Jing:"The blood is responsible for nourishing the body".
In addition, unobstructed flow of Qi through the vessels and the temperature of blood are closely related to the circulation of blood.
A passage from the chapter Jing Mai Bie Lun in Suwen says:"The nutritious part of the drink taken is absorbed in the stomach, then transported upward into the lungs by the spleen, afterwards dispersed to the whole body and partly sent down to the urinary bladder by the action of the lungs in regulating water metabolism, and in so doing the body fluid can be extensively spread out and flow in all channels".
The distribution and excretion of the body fluid are accomplished by the joint action of many Zang-Fu organs, chiefly the transportation of the spleen, dispersion and descent of the lungs, and warming-steaming and lifting clear-lowering turbid of the kidneys.
The body fluid takes the Tri-Jiao as its passageway for distribution and excretion.
And lastly by the control of blood circulation is meant that the flow of blood within the vessels instead of extravasating depends mainly upon the dominant action of Qi.
Thus blood is said to be "the mother of Qi".
The channels take a definite route, but the collaterals are widely distributed throughout the body like an interlacing network which combines all such structures of the body as the Zang-Fu organs, body orifices, skin, muscles, tendons and bones, into an integral whole.
The superficial collaterals are those which are located superficially and often emerge on the skin.
And the minute collaterals refer to all the tiny collaterals.
As the saying goes:"The Ren channel is responsible for the supply to fetus in the uterus".
The tiny collaterals branching off from the big ones are named"minute collaterals". As is described in the chapter Mai Du of Lingshu,"The little branches of the collaterals" are called minute collaterals.
For instance, a disease can be caused by such pathological products as six climate conditions in excess (wind, cold, summer-heat, dampness, dryness and fire), epidemic pathogenic factors, impairment due to seven emotions (joy, anger, melancholy, anxiety, grief, fear and terror).improper diet, overwork, various kinds of traumatic injuries, phlegm retention and blood stasis, all of which, therefore, constitute pathogenic factors.
Wind in excess, called wind pathogen, can cause disease.
Summer-heat in excess, causing disease, is known as pathogenic summer-heat.
This feature of damp disease refers to; a) damp syndrome marked by stickiness such as slimy and greasy stool and urine, greasy fur of the tongue, etc; b) a lingering disease difficult to cure, characterized by longer duration of illness or repeated attack, as often seen in eczema, damp arthralgia, etc.
It possesses the following features:(1) Pathogenic dryness, being dry in nature, is liable to impair body fluid.
However, heat is an exogenic pathogenic factor while fire an endogenic one.
The outflow of body fluid also results in consumption of Qi. Moreover, fire-pathogen tends to impair vital Qi, thus leading to general hypofunction and overfatigue.
Accumulated in a local spot, fire-pathogen is apt to bring about the stagnation of Qi and blood. Meanwhile, excessive fire will damage muscles and blood, thus resulting in large carbuncles and painful swelling on the body surface marked by localized swelling and burning pain in the wound or even suppuration and ulceration in it.
Furthermore, insufficiency of Qi and blood gives rise to deficiency of vital Qi and lowered body resistance, easily followed by other disorders.
By undue mental work are meant excessive meditation and anxiety which impair the heart and spleen.
Long-term divorce from physical activities tends to cause retardation of circulation of Qi and blood and hypofunction of the spleen and stomach manifested by anorexia, acratia, lassitude and weakness of the limbs, obesity or palpitation, shortness.of breath and sweating on slight exertion.
Such traumatic injuries as gunshot injuries, incised wounds, contusions, sprains and others may lead to blood stasis and painful swelling on the skin and muscles, bleeding or laceration of muscles and tendons, fracture and dislocation.
Burns and scalds are usually caused by high temperature objects, boiling water, scorching oil or fire, etc.
Slight burns and scalds only injure the skin, manifested as redness, swelling, fever or pain in the affected area while severe ones, if the surface of the wound is too large, are complicated by such symptoms as dysphoria, fever, thirst or oliguria or even death due to severe pain in the wound, internal invasion by fire-toxin, and evaporation or exudation of body fluid.
It is also referred to as a pathogenic factor because after its formation it may act directly or indirectly upon certain parts of the body, producing some new pathological changes in Zang-Fu organs and tissues manifested by various symptoms and signs.
These organs and tri-Jiao are closely related to circulation, distribution and excretion of water and fluid.
Its pathogenic characteristics are summarized as follows:(1) It obstructs the circulation of Qi and blood in the channels and vessels.
The retention of phlegm in the channels may block the circulation of Qi and blood, thus causing numbness of limbs, hemiplegia, etc. due to stagnation of Qi and blood.
Flowing into the Zang-Fu organs, phlegm may disturb the ascending or descending and entering or exiting functions of Qi, thus giving rise to other diseases.
Since Qi promotes the circulation of water, stagnation of Qi leads to retention of water in the body.
It refers to the extravasated blood accumulated within the body and the blood stagnated in channels and vessels and Zang-Fu organs due to impeded blood circulation.
Escaping blood, dark purplish in color, is mixed with clots.
Retention of extravasated blood may present many hemorrhagic symptoms such as hematemesis, hemoptysis bloody stool and urine, purpura on the skin, menorrhagia, metrorrhagia, etc.
Therefore, the onset of a disease iinvolves two aspects: vital Qi on the one hand and pathogens on the other.
Insufficiency of vital Qiis the intrinsic factor in the onset of a disease.
When vitalQi is sufficient, it is difficult for the pathogens to invade the body and no disease occurs.
For example, epidemic pathogenic factor, traumatic injury and others often play a leading role in the causation of disease independent of the condition of vital Qi.
When the disease occurs, it will manifest itself by different syndromes, depending on the disease-resisting power of vital Qi, virulence of pathogens, and severity of the disease as well as depth of the part affected.
For instance, an excess syndrome is present when vital Qi is powerful enough to destroy pathogens in desperate struggle against them while a deficiency syndrome occurs when vital Qi is insufficient or too weak to resist pathogens.
By internal environment is mainly meant vital Qi of the body proper.
Meanwhile, the resultant dysfunction of the Zang-Fu organs and channels and collaterals or derangement of Qi and blood can, in turn, bring about a variety of general or local pathological changes, manifested by everchanging clinical symptoms.
On the other hand, Qi and blood are the products of the fucntional activities of Zang-Fu organs, and, therefore, any pathological change they undergo will certainly influence Qi and blood, thus giving rise to pathological changes of Qi and blood.
Deficiency of Qi, leading to hypofunction of various organs, is manifested by such symptons as listlessness, lassitude, spontaneous sweating, and susceptibility to cold.
Since Qi bears a close relationship with blood and body fluid, deficiency of Qi is bound to affect the generation, transportation and distribution of blood and body fluid, thereby giving rise to many pathological changes of blood and body fluid.
Stagnated Qi, however, will make blood and water stop flowing, thereby producing such morbid products as blood stasis and phlegm retention.
Therefore, blood stasis, phlegm and stagnation of Qi turn out to be the cause and effect of each other in turn.
Since the liver (responsible for ascending function), the lungs (for descending function), the spleen (for ascending function) and the stomach (for descending function) all play an extremely important role in the regulation of functional activities of the human body, dysfunction of these organs often causes the stangnation of Qi, as is often seen in obstruction of the lung-Qi, and stangation of the liver-Qi, of the spleen and stomach-Qi.
The liver, an energetic Zang-organ, maintains potency for the flow of Qi and storage of blood, therefore.upward invasion of the hyperactive liver-Qi leads to hemoptysis and haematesis due to the reversed flow of Qi, or even to syncope due to disturbance of Qi in the brain.
Because the spleen, as the source of growth and development of Qi and blood, performs the function of sending up essential nutrients, its insufficiency is more likely to cause Qi collapse, commonly known as collapse of the spleen-Qi or sinking of Qi of the middie-Jiao{a general term for the spleen and the stomach).
Qi-collapse brought about by deficiency syndrome, is usually manifested by some symptoms of deficiency type, such as abdominal distention with tenesmus, frequent feeling of stool, shortness of breath, listlessness, weak voice, weak pulse, etc. in addition to ptoses of some of the Zang-organs.
The external exbaustion of Qi due to its inability to stay internally reuslts from failure of vital Qi to ward off pathogens or from prolonged weakening of vital Qi or from exhaustion of Qi caused by massive bleeding or profuse sweat, etc.
Actually, exhaustion of Qi is the leading pathogenesis of various prostration syndromes.
For instance, weakness of the spleen and stomach, malnutrition and no substance from which blood is generated result in inadequate formation of blood; while the resultant massive hemorrhage or slow and unconscious consumption of nutritive Qi and blood due to chronic illness brings about excessive consumption of blood, thereby leading to deficiency of blood.
Since the Zang-Fu organs and tissues, channels and collaterals depend on blood for their nourishment, deficiency of blood may lead to such weak syndromes of deficiency type as general or localized malnutrition, gradual decline of functinal activities, etc.
It is due chiefly to stagnation of Qi, deficiency of Qi, blood-cold, blood-heat and retention of phlegm in the interior as well.
Since stagnant blood is the pathological product of blood stasis, it may be obstructed in channels and collaterals after its formation, thus serving as one of the causes of blood stasis.
It is caused by attack of blood by heat pathognes and by fire pathogen transfomed by emotionai disorders due to mental depression.
Heat in the blood system and forced flow of blood by heat may speed up the flow of blood and burn channels and vessels. resulting in various kinds of bleeding due to blood-heat.
Meanwhile, invasion of blood by heat pathogens decocts blood and body fluid.
Normal production, distribution and excrection of body fluid are inseparable from ascending or descending and incoming or outgoing movements of Qi and its functional activities, transporting and transforming function of the spleen, dispersing und descending function of the lungs, water-regulating function of the kidneys and clearance and regulation of water passage by tri-Jiao.
Disharmony and imbalance of the movement of Qi. or functional disturbance of Qi, the spleen, lungs, kidneys or tri-Jiao all may give rise to disturbance in fluid metabolism, thus producing such pathological changes as insufficiency of body fluid or retention of phlegm and accumulation of dampness.
Insufficiency of body fluid is mostly attributable to consumption of body fluid by pathogenic dryness-heat and disorders of five emotions, or profuse perspiration, vomiting, diarrhea, loss of blood or excessive intake of drugs of acrid taste and drying effect. etc.
By disturbance in distribution of body fluid is meant that it cannot be normally distributed, leading to sluggish circulation and local accumulation of dampness, which is transformed into phlegm retention.
Owing to the fact that in case of disturbance in sweat discharge, waste fluid left after metabolism still can be transformed into urine to be discharged from the body, the kidneys are said to govern the excretion of body fluid.
To sum up functional disturbance of the kidneys and disturbance in formation and discharge of urine will eventually lead to water retention thus forming edema.
As body fluid and blood are the carrier of Qi, loss of body fluid will deprive Qi of its lodgement and Qiwillbe exhausted externall as well.
As body fluid and blood, derived from the same source, are mutually permeable, loss of body fluid because of nigh fever, burns, vomiting, diarrhea, profuse perspiration, etc., will cause hypovolemia and sluggish circulation of blood, leading to blood stasis.
In addition to clinical manifestations, such as insufficiency of body fluid, there are such symptoms of blood stasis as purplish tongue, or petechia ecchymosis, or skin eruption.
As the spleen has the function to transport and transform water, dysfunction of the spleen in transport is a leading cause of production of turbid dampness in the interior.
For instance, stagnation of liver-Qi gives rise to liver-fire.
Therefore, pathogenesis of Zang-Fu organs occupies an important place in the theory of pathogenesis, and forms the foundation of"treatment based on differential diagnosis".
When fire of deficiency type attacks the blood vessels, there will be such symptoms as red tongue and small rapid pulse.
In severe cases. there may appear stagnation and blockage of Qi and blood, manifested by severe palpitation, sudden attack of pain in the precordium, even cold limbs in severe cases, deep-seated pulse, and syncope after profuse sweating.
However, weakened dispersing function and impairment of purifying and descending function of the lungs may influence each other in the pathologic process, either of which may cause abnormal rising of the lung-Qi, giving rise to cough and dyspnea, or disturbance in water metabolism manifested by edema and oliguria.
Due to dysfunction of the kidneys, the kidnely-essence is easily lost, thus leading to seminal emission and spermatorrhea.
The stomach-cold leads to sluggish functional activities of Qi and contraction of meridians, often marked by severe epigastric pain which is relieved by warmth.
It is mainly due to attack of the stomach by pathogenic heat; or to indulgence in alcoholic drinks, preference for hot, pungent food, excessive intake of food rich in fat, which produces heat; or to accumulation of heat in the stomach which is transformed from stagnated Qi, blood stasis, and retention of phlegm or food.
The stomach heat gives rise to hyperfunction of the stomach, marked by unpleasant hungry sensation, excessive appetite, etc.
When the fire transformed from the stomach-heat flares up, it leads to adverse rising of the stomach-Qi, marked bly nausea and acid regurgitation.
Furthermore when the fire impairs the vessels of the stomach, the blood flows upward to produce hematemesis.
The diagnostic method aims at collecting various symptoms and signs manifested by a disease by means of the four diagnostic techniques and then at finding out its cause and pathogenesis, thereby providing a basis for selection of treatment.
All visible signs related to the disease are within the scope of inspection.
In addition rashes uneven in density or quickly disappearing are generally regarded as the critical symptom due to insufficiency of vital Qi and invasion of the interior of the body by pathogens.
Observation of the tongue includes inspection of the tongue proper, which consists of muscles, vessels, etc and that of the tongue fur, a layer of fur-like substance covering the surface of the tongue and formed by steaming of the stomach-Qi.
For instance the pale and moist tongue with tooth prints at its borders usually suggests an excess of cold-dampness whereas the pink tongue with tooth marks on its margin, hypofunction of the spleen or insufficiency of Qi.
Pathologically, the purplish-red and wry tongue, associated with acute symptoms, most probably suggests convulsions due to intense liver-wind, while the reddish and wry tongue, accompanied by chronic symptoms, usually indicates hemiplegia due to apoplexy.
The deeper the yellow of the tongue fur, the more intense the pathogenic heat.
Observation of discharges aims chiefly at examining their changes in appearance, colour, amount and nature, so as to find out pathological changes of the Zang-Fu organs.
For instance, bright-red venules usually indicate attack of exogenous pathogens such as wind and cold; purplish-red venules, heat-syndrome; bluish venules, windsyndrome or pain-syndrome; bluish-purple, or purplish-black venules denote a critical stage due to blockade of superficial venules, and pale venules, deficiency of the spleen.
Since the lungs control the Qi of the body, the kidneys regulate inspiration and the heart governs speech, the voice is most closely related to the organs mentioned above.
Paroxymal rapid respiration with wheezing is named asthma; breathing shorter and quicker than that of normal people, with difficulty in going on respiration like dyspnea but without elevated shoulder, and with rapid breath but without wheezing, is called shortness of breath, oppressive and stuffy sensation in the chest with frequent moaning and groaning is named sigh due to stagnation of the liver-Qi.
Scanty, foul and dark yellow urine frequently indicates damp-heat syndrome and urine smell in the ward is often seen in the late stage of serious edema. Lastly, foul smell like the odour of rotten apple from the mouth is attributable to diabetes.
When questioning, a doctor must be amiable without dropping any hint and avoid upseting the patient.
Cold and heat due to exogenous pathogens often occur simultaneously, while either due to internal injury appears separately.
Since abnormal perspirations vary with the nature of pathogens and degree of deficiency of vital Qi, questioning about perspiration may help the doctor to differentiate the varied morbid states, such as asthenic or sthenic syndrome, superficial orinterior syndrome and cold or heat syndrome.
Interrogation of perspiration consists mainly of hyperhidrosis or anhidrosis, the site, time, amount, colour and nature of sweating.
In a critically ill patient, sweating following sever chills involving the whole body is.called perspiration after shivering.
If high fever persists after sweating, accompanied by irritability and swift pulse, the disease is likely to be aggravated as a result of conquest of vital Qi by pathogens
The pathogenic agents contributing to it may be wind-phlegm, or blood stasis phlegm, or wind-dampness, often seen in patients with apoplexy, flaccidity syndrome or paralysis.
The acute headache involving the nape and back which is aggravated by exposure to wind mostly suggests exogenous disease due to invasion of pathogenie wind-cold; distending headache accompanied by flushed complexion and conjunctival congestion is due to exogenous attack of pathogenic wind-heat, and heaviness sensation in the head like being tightly bound, accompanied by chilliness and fever, is caused by exogenous attack of pathogenic wind-dampness.
Wandering pain in the joints known as migratory arthralgia is predominantlly due to pathogenic wind; acute and intolerable pain called painful arthnalgia is mainly caused by attack of the pathogenic cold; heavy feeling of the affected area and localized pain called fixed arthralgia is due chiefly to pathogenic dampness; and redness, swelling, heat and pain of the joint, accompanied by fever and thirst, called heat-type arthralgia is due to heat transformation from dampness.
At the early stage of dampness-warm syndrome, there must be pain and heaviness of the body, and downward flow of damp-heat may bring about the heaviness of lower limbs and difficulty in walking.
Pricking headache suggests blood stasis in the head due mostiy to trauma, stabbing pain in the chest usually indicates obstruction of the heart blood; twinge in the hypochondrium mostly indicates long depression of liver-Qi and obstruction of blood circulation; and prickle in the lower abdomen is indicative of blood stasis in the lower-Jiao, often associated with disorders of menses in women.
Chest pain radiating to the back or back pain to the chest, accompanied by sweating, cold limbs and faint indistinct pulse indicates chest Bi-syndrome, and distending pain in the right hypochondrium radiating to the right shoulder, is indicative of dampness and heat in the liver and gallbladder.
Dysfunction of the spleen and stomach or affection of the spleen by other diseases are reflected on diet and taste.
Tastelessness in the mouth is caused by deficiency of the spleen-Qi and stomach-Qi; sweet taste with stickiness in the mouth suggests accumulation of dampness-heat in the spleen and stomach; sour taste in the mouth indicates the depressed heat in the liver and stomach: acid regurgitation with foul breath signifies indigestion; and, finally, bitter taste in the mouth is usually indicative of overabundance of the gallbladder-fire.
Profuse or persistent vaginal disharge with whitish and clear tinge, called leukorrhea is seepage of dampness due to spleen-asthenia; yellowish, viscid and foul discharge from the vagina, called yellowish leukorrhagia, to downward flow of damp-heat; and leukorrhagia with blood and pus, called reddish leukorrhagia, mostly to stagnated heat of the liver channel.
The three pulse conditions are known as the Cun pulse, Guan pulse and Chi pulse respectively.
However, in other times, pulse can also be felt.
Generally speaking, pulse-feeling requires a quiet environment and a patient in a calm mood with stable Qi and blood in order for an accurate diagnosis to be made.
Recognition of pulse condition is made usually through applying three grades of finger forces on the three pulse regions.
Strenuous exercise, emotional excitement, eating and drinking often cause the pulse to speed up.
The deep and forceful pulse indicates an interior-excess syndrome in which. the pathogens accumulate in the interior and Qi and blood are stagnated, while the deep and forceless pulse suggests an interior-deficiency syndrome, in which weakness of Zang-Fu organs and insufficiency of Qi and blood lead to inability of channel-Qi to be activated.
General Comment on Deficiency and Excess of Suwen says, "An excess syndrome results when the invading pathogens are exuberant.
Slow but vigorous pulse palpated in a well-trained athlete is considered as normal.
Because excessiveness of heat inside the body brings about accumulation of Qi and blood and dilation of the vessels, the pulse becomes large, floating and forceful, and the beat comes vigorously and goes gently.
If full pulse appears in a protracted disease with consumption of Qi, loss of blood, or protracted diarrhea etc, it suggests a crisis due to violence of pathogens and deficiency of vital Qi.
When the liver and gallbladder are troubled, the function may be impaired, losing the moderation of the liver-Qi, thereby, forming the taut pulse.
It also appears in wind syndrome, pain syndrome, persistent and violent emotions and trauma due to suspension of channel-Qi, which should not be considered as severe conditions.
Attention should be paid to the running, thready and weak pulse, which is indicative of prostratin syndrome.
A pulse composed of two or more pulse conditions existing simultaneouly is called coexisting pulse.
Generally speaking, a coexisting pulse indicates a collection of diseases that each single pulse is indicative of.
Since its condition is peculiar and quite different from ordinary pulse condition, it is also named strange pulse.
Wei yilin, a distinguished physician of the Yuan Dynasty, described ten strange, or moribund, pulses in his workShi Yi De Xiao Fang.
They include knife edge pulse, pea-rolling pulse and confused running pulse, in addition to the above seven moribund pulses.
This refers to a nearly imperceptible pulse with occasional dartilng beats which resemble a shrimp darting in water, one of the ten moribund pulses.
'This is one of the ten moribund pulses, deep solid yet forceless, resembling flicking a stone with finger tips, which indicates exhaustion of the kidney-Qi.
The blockage of the pericardium by retained fluid may also cause indistinct Xuli pulse.
In addition, palpation of acupoints may also be applied in a tentative treatment for the purpose of differential diagnosis.
For instance, pressing bilateral Danshu (B 39) points can relieve abdominal pain due to biliary ascariasis, but proves of no effect in other cases of abdominal pain.
It is sudden in onset, superficial and mild in nature, and short in duration without affecting the function of Zang-Fu organs in most cases.
In general, it includes almost all the syndromes other than the exterior syndrome.
The interior syndrome may be produced by the exogenous pathogons which either enter the interior from the superficies or directly invade the Zang-Fu organs; or by some other factors, such as emotional upset, improper diet or overstrain, which affect the functions of Zang-Fu organs.
It refers to the invasion of pathogens from the superficial part of the body to the deep, or the replacement of exterior syndrome by interior one.
It means that cold syndrome is intertwined with heat syndrome in one and the same patient.
For example, a disease at its onset manifests itself by cold syndrome followed by heat syndrome, and the former vanishes as soon as the latter appears.
This is what is known as transformation of cold syndrome into heat syndrome, as in the case of exterior cold syndrome due to exogenous pathogens, marked by such symptoms as fever, chilly sensation, no sweat, headache, general aching, thin whitish fur of the tongue, tense floating pulse, etc.
This is what is called transformation of heat syndrome into cold syndrome, as in the case of a patient with high fever who, due to delayed treatment or misdiagnosis, may be overcome by pathogenic factor which prevails over vital Qi and suddenly develops such symptoms as cold limbs, profuse cold sweat, listlessness, and faint indistinct pulse.
It is different from cold syndrome in that the patient's body is warm in spite of cold limbs, and he or she has an aversion to heat instead of cold, and his or her pulse is deep, but also rapid and forceful.
For example. improper diet may lead to weakness of the physique; emotional upsets. may impair Qi and blood of Zang-Fu organs; sexual indulgence may consume the kidney Qi; and prolonged illness may impair vital Qi.
Treatment must vary, depending on the type the syndrome pertains to.
For example, deficiency of the spleen-Qi and lung-Qi leads to dysfunction of the spleen and lungs manifested by formation of substantial pathogens, such as phlegm, fluidrelention, water and dampness.
It is a syndrome of deficiency type, but accompanied by symptoms similar to excess syndrome.
However, upon careful examination it may be found that abdominal distension, which is not persistent, now slight, now severe, can be relieved by pressure, and that the patient's pulse is taut but weak, indicating that insufficiency of Qi and blood of Zang-Fu organs is the real essence of disease, whereas symptoms similar to excess syndrome are but false phenomena.
It is a syndrome resulting from tight closure of striae of tho skin and muscles due to invasion of the superficies by exogenous pathogens manifested by fever, chills, headache, general aching, stuffy nose, no sweat, and tense floating pulse.
The manifestations, etiology. pathogenesis and treatment of the six principal syndromes have already been dealt with respectively in the previous sections.
State of Qi, Blood and Body Fluid It is a diagnostic method with which to analyse the pathologic changes of Qi, blood and body fluid, and identify the nature of a disease according to the part of Zang-Fu doctrine dealing with Qi, blood and body fluid.
This syndrome is mostly used to denote functional disturbance of the lungs, stomach and liver, for it often iinvolves these organs.
Abnormal ascending of the lung-Qi is manifested as cough and dyspnea; that of the stomach-Qi as hiccup, belching, nausea and vomiting; and that of the liver-Qi as distending pain of the head and eyes, dizziness, or even syncope and hematemesis.
It refers to blood stasis due to stagnation and depression of Qi, related mainly todysfunction of the liver caused by emotional upsets.
It refers to a morbid condition due to insufficiency of body fluid which leads to its inability to nourish the whole body or some Zang-Fu organs.
It is a syndrome caused by pathogenic cold combined with phlegm, and by abundant expectoration accompanied by cold manifestations.
Since the methods of differential diagnosis employed in clinical practice are many and varied, each having its own characteristics, they must first be applied to Zang-Fu organs so as to definitely determine the site and nature of a disease and adopt a treatment accordingly.
It is a syndrome of inability of the spleen to keep blood flowing within the vessels owing to insufficiency of the spleen-Qi.
This is a syndrome characterized by inability of the liver to disperse Qi.
This is a syndrome marked by adverse rising of Qi and fire from theliver.
Its clinical manifestations are: dizziness, distending headache, flushed face, conjunctival congestion, bitter taste, dry mouth, restlessness and irritability, insomnia, nightmare, burning pain in the hypochondrium, constipation, dark urine, tinnitus, otopyorrhea, hematemesis, epistaxis, red tongue with yellow fur, and taut rapid pulse.
This refers to a syndrome due to consumption of the kidney-essence.
This is a morbid condition attributable to inccordination between water (the kidneys) and ire (the heart).
Its clinical manifestations are: cough with scanty sputum or blood-tinged sputum, dry throat and mouth, hoarseness. emaciation, weakness of the loins and knees, hectic and regular recurrent fever, flushed cheeks, night sweating, seminal emission in males, irregular menstruation in females, red tongue with little fur, and thready rapid pulse.
Its clinical menifestations are: Dizziness, tinnitus resembling the sound of a cicada, dull pain in the hypochondium, amnesia, insomnia, weakness of the loins and knees, dry throat and mouth, dysphoria wih feverish sensation in the chest, palms and soles, flushed cheeks, night sweating, seminal emission in males, scanty menstruation in females, red tongue with little fur and thready rapid pulse.
This syndrome refers to insufficiency of the spleen-Qi and the lung-Qi.
This syndrome is the result of stagnation of the liver-Qi and dysfunction of the spleen in transport.
This syndrome is indicative of dysfunction of both the liver and the stomach.
This is a syndrome due to upward invasion of the lungs by the Qi and fire in the liver leading to pulmonary dysfunction in purification and descent.
It usually results from the fire produced by the stagnation of the liver-Qi due to emotional depression or from invasion of the lungs by the adverse rising fire produced by the stagnation of pathogenic heat in the liver channel.
Its clinical manifestations are: abdominal fullness, vomiting, anorexia, diarrhea, no thirst, frequent abdominal pain, whitish fur on the tongue, weak and moderate pulse.
The chapter Tong Ping Xu Shi Lun Treatise on General Comment of Deficiency and Excess of Suwen also points out: "Exhaustion of vital essence brings about deficiency syndrome.
In case of invasion of blood by excessive heat, there may appear skin eruptions, hemoptysis, epistaxis, and hematochezia, In case of wind-syndrome due to excessive heat, convulsion and syncope happen as a result.
Since pathogenic dampness is closely related to the spleen and stomach, there also appears the syndrome of disturbance of the spleen and stomach due to invasion by pathogenic dampness and its retention in the muscles, besides the exterior-sydnrome.
Since the occurrence of a disease iinvolves both the vital Qi and pathogenic factors, prevention of a disease must start with enhancing the resistance of vital Qi to pathogenic factors and with preventing the invasion of the human body by pathogens.
It is a specific therapeutic principle regarding treatment of a disease in accordance with its false signs.
It is a method for the treatment of pseudo-heat syndromes with drugs of hot nature.
It is a method of treating pseudo-cold diseases with drugs of cold nature.
For example, the symptom of cold limbs due to excess of heat marked by cold limbs and deep pulse seems to be cold-syndrome, but is accompanied by high fever, feeling of restlessness over the chest, scanty dark urine, etc.
To support vital Qi is to strengthen body resistance.
Since victory or failure in the struggle between vital Qi and pathogens determines the development or termination of a disease, one of the important principles underlying clinical therapy is to change the relative strength of vital Qi and pathogens, making the illness take a turn for the better.
To support vital Qi is to restore vital Qi in most cases, which is indicated in deficiency syndrome, in which deficiency of vital Qi is the primary contradiction, whilc pathogens are not dominant or have been declining.
In this case, if the method of eliminating pathogens is simultaneously applied, vital Qi will be further damaged instead of being supported.
The human body is an organic whole, in which Zang-organs and Fu-organs coordinate and promote each other physiologically and interact on each other pathologically.
When any of the Zang-Fu organs doesn't function well, all the other organs may be affected.
Thus, when treating a disorder of any Zang-Fu organ, we consider not merely the diseased organ alone, but take into account the interrelationship between all Zang-Fu organs instead.
For instance, a disorder of the lungs may result either from an attack of pathogens on themselves or from dysfunction of the heart, liver, spleen, kidneys and the large intestine.
" By syndrome of deficiency nature is meant deficient vital Qi, or a pathological reaction with deficient vital Qi, as the principal aspect of the contradiction.
The therapeutical principle underlying administration of drugs according to age, sex, physique, different modes of living of patients etc. is known as treatment in accordance with constitution of an individual.
